# Bugs Life Simulation C++

## Overview
This project is a console-based bug life simulation written in C++.  
The program loads bugs from a text file and simulates their movement, battles, health, and survival on a 10x10 board.

The application demonstrates important Object-Oriented Programming concepts including:
- Inheritance
- Polymorphism
- Abstract classes
- Virtual functions
- Encapsulation
- File handling
- Dynamic memory allocation

---

# Features

## Bug Types
The simulation contains multiple bug types:

### Crawler
Moves one step in a direction.

### Hopper
Moves multiple spaces depending on hop length.

### DiagonalBug
Moves diagonally across the board.

---

# Main Features

## Load Bugs From File
Bug data is loaded from `bugs.txt`.

Example format:
```txt
C;101;0;0;4;10
H;102;9;0;1;8;2
D;107;4;4;1;20
Display All Bugs

Shows:

Bug ID
Type
Position
Direction
Health
Alive/Dead status
Find Bug

Searches for a bug by ID and displays its information.

Tap Board

Simulates one movement step:

Bugs randomly turn direction
One random bug becomes frozen
Remaining bugs move
Fight System

When bugs occupy the same position:

They fight for up to 3 rounds
Random damage is applied
Bugs can die during combat
Display Life History

Shows every position visited by each bug during the simulation.

Display All Cells

Displays every board coordinate and shows which bugs occupy each cell.

Run Simulation

Automatically runs the simulation:

Tracks tap count
Freezes random bugs each tap
Handles bug movement and combat
Stops when:
one bug remains alive OR
maximum tap count is reached

At the end:

surviving/winning bug is displayed
life history is saved to an output file
Save Life History

Life history is saved automatically to timestamped .out files.

Example:

bugs_life_history_20260507_192455.out
Object-Oriented Programming Concepts
Inheritance

All bug types inherit from the abstract Bug base class.

Polymorphism

Bugs are stored as:

std::vector<Bug*>

Virtual functions allow different movement behaviour.

Abstract Class

Bug contains pure virtual functions:

virtual void move() = 0;
Encapsulation

Bug data is protected/private and accessed using getters/setters.

